{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> θήρ</b>, θηρός, <br /> <i>Epic dialect</i> <i>dative</i> <i>plural</i> θήρεσσι, ὁ: later also ἡ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus “De Natura Animalium - Ar.Byzantine Epit.” 6.24, etc.: (see. entry near the end)\">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]:— <b>beast of prey</b>, especially a lion (so used in Cephallenia, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" Scholia 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.324), 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.586, etc.\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ Νέμειος θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Hercules Furens” 153: coupled with λέων, [prev. work] 465, 6th c.BC: Epimenides Philosophus 2: with λέαινα, “Anthologia Graeca” 14.63.4 (2nd c.AD: Mesomedes Lyricus) \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; of the wild boar, Ἐρυμάνθιος θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 1097 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of Cerberus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “OC” 1569 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs</a>]; ὁ θ., of a hind, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “El.” 572 \">Refs</a>]: <i>plural</i>, generally, <b>beasts</b>, opposed to birds and fishes, ἠέ που ἐν πόντῳ φάγον ἰσθύες, ἢ ἐπὶ χέρσου θηρσὶ καὶ οἰωνοῖσιν ἕλωρ γένετ᾽ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 24.291; ἰχθύσι μὲν καὶ θηρσὶ καὶ οἰωνοῖς πετεηνοῖς 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 277; ἐν θηρσίν, ἐν βροτοῖσιν, ἐν θεοῖς ἄνω 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 941.12; ἐν ἄγρῃ θηρῶν 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.129; ἄφοβοι θῆρες 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Ajax” 366: _metaphorically_, θῆρες ξιφήρεις\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>], of Orestes and Pylades, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Orestes” 1272, compare “Ph.” 1296 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἡ σφοδρότης.. θηρός (i.e. Ἔρωτος) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Alexander Rhetor 245.12: proverbial, ἔγνω θὴρ θῆρα 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Rhetorica” 1371b16. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> of any <b>living creature</b>, πλωτοὶ θῆρες, i.e. dolphins, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Arion Lyricus 1.5 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; of <b>vermin</b> killed by birds, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Aves” 1064 (Lyric poetry) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of gnats, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"“Anthologia Graeca” 5.150 (1st c.BC: Meleager Epigrammaticus) \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; of the <b>sacred animals</b> in Egypt, ἀρχιστολιστὴς θηρῶν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Sammelb.” 4011.4. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> any fabulous <b>monster</b>, as the Sphinx, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Septem contra Thebas” 558 codices \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; especially of a centaur, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 556, 568 (compare φήρ) \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; of Satyrs, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Cyclops” 624 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; οὐ θεῶν τις οὐδ᾽ ἄνθρωπος οὐδὲ θ. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Eumenides” 70.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>] —Less frequently than θηρίον in Prose, but found in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus [prev. cited] (variant{θηρίων}), 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 4.6.4, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 559d, “Sph.” 235a, 2nd-3rd c.AD: Aelianus [same place], etc.; ἄγριοι θῆρες 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Ethica Eudemia” 1229a25. (I.- 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>ĝh[uglide]ēr-</b>, compare φήρ, Lithuanian <i>žvėrìs</i> 'wild beast'.)","strongNumber":"G7668","accentedUnicode":"θήρ","shortDef":"a wild beast","mediumDef":"a wild b